{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/depression/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"d34c93b9-e882-588a-8711-b0acdcba167b","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 8f80499e-f728-4ef8-aafd-a70400c73e2f --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field 8f80499e-f728-4ef8-aafd-a70400c73e2f -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 2d9f76d5-17c6-40a8-8afc-a70400c73cba --><!-- begin field e1da4e2e-e380-4535-9622-a70400c73e2f --><ul><li><strong>Depressive</strong> disorders are very common and are among the leading causes of disability worldwide. In people aged 18-44 years, depression is the leading cause of disability and premature death. <ul><li>Depression is predicted to be the second leading cause of disability in people of all ages by the year 2020.</li></ul></li><li>The worldwide prevalence of depression is estimated to be 4.4% and prevalence in the UK is 4.5%.<ul><li>The total number of people living with depression increased by 18.4% between 2005 and 2015.</li></ul></li><li>Prevalence varies with age and sex, peaking in older adults (7.5% in females and 5.5% among males aged 55–74 years). </li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/depression/references/\">WHO, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/depression/references/\">BMJ, 2019</a>]</p><!-- end field e1da4e2e-e380-4535-9622-a70400c73e2f --><!-- end item 2d9f76d5-17c6-40a8-8afc-a70400c73cba -->","topic":{"id":"5f794dff-eed8-52d6-bb65-1b1a9b1fc50a","topicId":"1b270734-f24e-4b58-8355-adaec350f356","topicName":"Depression","slug":"depression","lastRevised":"Last revised in February 2021","chapters":[{"id":"b34732f5-da05-5558-ac7e-4169aea1302d","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"bd7d7dbf-c3a1-5690-8d7b-8fe76ab04a16","fullItemName":"Have I got t